]<br>[[Southwest Asia Service Medal]]<br> Joint Chiefs of Staff Badge\n}}\n'''Peter Graham Olson''' (born December 9, 1962) is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|TX|22}}, serving since 2009. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. The district includes much of southeastern [[Houston, Texas|Houston]], as well as most of the city's southern suburbs such as [[Katy, Texas|Katy]], [[Pearland]], and [[Sugar Land]].\n\n==Early life, education, and military service==\nPeter Graham Olson was born in 1962 in [[Fort Lewis, Washington]].  In 1972, Olson moved with his family to [[Seabrook, Texas]], a suburb of [[Houston]], where he attended public schools, graduating from [[Clear Lake High School (Houston, Texas)|Clear Lake High School]] in 1981.  Olson attended college at [[Rice University]], where he played college basketball his freshman year; he earned  a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in [[computer science]] in 1985. He subsequently attended  [[University of Texas School of Law|law school]] at the [[University of Texas at Austin]], receiving his [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] and being admitted to the State Bar of Texas in  1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.texasbar.com/AM/Template.cfm?Section=Find_A_Lawyer&template=/Customsource/MemberDirectory/MemberDirectoryDetail.cfm&ContactID=230645 |publisher=State Bar of Texas|accessdate=February 26, 2017 |title=MR. PETER G. OLSON |work=Find a Lawyer}}</ref> He joined the [[United States Navy]] after graduating from law school and earned his [[Naval Aviator]] wings in March 1991. After earning his wings as a [[P-3C Orion]] pilot, post-[[Gulf War]], he flew missions over the [[Persian Gulf]], the [[Indian Ocean]], and the [[Pacific Ocean|Pacific]]. In 1994, he was assigned as a Naval liaison to the [[United States Senate]], during which time he assisted Republican U.S. Senator [[Phil Gramm]] on several overseas trips.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}  He served in the Navy for nine years.\n\n==Early political career==\nAfter leaving active military duty, he joined Senator Gramm's staff in 1998. After Gramm's retirement from the Senate in 2002, Olson served as chief of staff to Gramm's successor, U.S. Senator and former [[Attorney General of Texas|Texas Attorney General]] [[John Cornyn]], from December 2002 until May 2007.<ref name=WSJ_Eaton_20080721a>{{cite web|first=Leslie|last=Eaton|title=GOP Goes on Offensive For DeLay's Old Seat|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB121660293928869273?mod=googlenews_wsj|work=[[Wall Street Journal]]|date=July 21, 2008|accessdate=August 10, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n===Elections===\n====2008====\n{{main|Texas's 22nd congressional district election, 2008}}\nOlson defeated [[incumbent]] [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] Representative [[Nick Lampson]] in the general election on November 4, 2008. Olson received 53% of the vote and Lampson received 45%.<ref>{{cite news|first=Suzanne|last=Gamboa|title=Olson upends Lampson in closely watched race|url=http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/APStories/stories/D948JSCG0.html|work=Dallas Morning News|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=November 5, 2008|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081108101631/http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/APStories/stories/D948JSCG0.html|archivedate=November 8, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. House, Texas 22, Results by District|url=http://www.cnn.com/ELECTION/2008/results/individual/#mapHTX/H/22|work=CNN|accessdate=November 5, 2008}}</ref> Olson won the Republican nomination by defeating former Congresswoman [[Shelley Sekula-Gibbs]] in the April 8, 2008, run-off election.<ref>{{cite news|first=Mike|last=Tolson|title=Olson scores victory against Sekula Gibbs, He'll battle Democratic candidate Nick Lampson in general election for District 22 seat|url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/front/5685798.html|work=Fort Bend County News|publisher=Houston Chronicle|date=April 9, 2008|accessdate=May 25, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"CQ_4-09\">Greg Giroux, [http://www.cqpolitics.com/wmspage.cfm?docID=news-000002699618 \"Texas GOP Runoff Goes to Ex-Senate Aide in Race for DeLay\u2019s Old Seat\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081030112528/http://www.cqpolitics.com/wmspage.cfm?docID=news-000002699618 |date=October 30, 2008 }}, ''CQ Politics'', April 9, 2008.</ref>\n[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] candidate [[Nick Lampson]] won in 2006 when the 11-term Republican incumbent, former [[Party leaders of the United States House of Representatives|House Majority Leader]] [[Tom DeLay]], was [[indicted]]. DeLay's resignation came too late for another Republican to replace him on the ballot, so Lampson defeated a Republican running as a [[write-in candidate]].\n\nAn October 22, 2008, poll by [[John Zogby]] and ''[[The Houston Chronicle]]'' stated that Olson had a 17-point lead over Lampson.<ref>{{cite news|first=Easha|last=Anand|title=Down the Homestretch: Texas's 22nd District (Democratic Incumbent)|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2008/10/27/down-the-homestretch-texass-22nd-district-democratic-incumbent|work=Wall Street Journal|date=October 28, 2008|accessdate=October 28, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Jason|last=Thurlkill|title=Houston Chronicle/Zogby: Olson has 17 point lead over Lampson, Culberson holding off Skelly|url=http://www.politickertx.com/node/373|work=PolitickerTX.com|date=October 27, 2008|accessdate=October 28, 2008}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Houston Politics|url=http://blogs.chron.com/houstonpolitics/zogby_mon_results_22nd_tabs.pdf|format=PDF|work=Zogby International|publisher=Houston Chronicle|date=October 22, 2008|accessdate=October 28, 2008|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081029021615/http://blogs.chron.com/houstonpolitics/zogby_mon_results_22nd_tabs.pdf|archivedate=October 29, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On October 30, 2008, [[Larry Sabato]] predicted in the [[Sabato's Crystal Ball|Crystal Ball]] that Olson's congressional race would be a race that would be a \"Republican Pick Up.\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Larry|last=Sabato|title=The Last Word \u2013 Almost|work=Rassamussen Reports|date=October 30, 2008|accessdate=October 30, 2008|url=http://www.rasmussenreports.com/public_content/political_commentary/commentary_by_larry_j_sabato/the_last_word_almost}}</ref> Lampson was considered the most vulnerable Democratic incumbent in the House because of the heavily Republican tilt of the district. With a [[Cook Partisan Voting Index]] of R+15, it was the fourth most Republican district in the nation to be represented by a Democratic representative.  U.S. President [[George W. Bush]] carried the 22nd with 64% of the vote in 2004.{{citation needed|date=October 2013}}\n\nDue to the unusual circumstances in District 22, the race attracted national attention. In 2007, [[Stuart Rothenberg]] called the district \"arguably the best Republican takeover opportunity in the country\".<ref name=Rothenberg_20070622>{{cite journal|first=Stuart|last=Rothenberg|title=Texas 22: Top of the List|work=The Rothenberg Political Report|volume=30 |issue=12 |date=June 22, 2007|url=http://rothenbergpoliticalreport.blogspot.com/2007/06/new-print-edition-missouri-6-texas-22.html|accessdate=May 25, 2008}}</ref> After Olson was nominated, the [[Electoral-vote.com]] website identified his campaign as \"probably the GOP's best pickup opportunity for 2008.\"<ref name=\"Hot House Races in 2008\">{{cite web|title=Hot House Races in 2008|publisher=Electoral-vote.com|url=http://electoral-vote.com/evp2008/House/house_races.html|accessdate=May 25, 2008}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]'', a leading [[Washington, D.C.]] political newspaper, opined that Olson's victory over Sekula Gibbs has set \"up one of the top House races in the country in a conservative [[Houston, Texas|Houston]] district.\"<ref name=TheHill_Blake_20080408a>{{cite news|first=Aaron|last=Blake|title=Olson tops Sekula Gibbs in Texas runoff|work=''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]''|date=April 8, 2008|url=http://thehill.com/campaign-2008/olson-tops-sekula-gibbs-in-texas-runoff-2008-04-08.html|accessdate=June 7, 2008|quote='Nick Lampson better find himself a flashlight because his reelection chances are quickly growing dim', said Ken Spain, a spokesman for the [[National Republican Congressional Committee]], adding that 'Pete Olson has proven himself to be one of the top Republican challengers in the country and we believe he has exactly what it takes to win in November.'}}</ref><ref name=DallasMorningNews_Gilman_20080511>{{cite news|last=Gilman|first=Todd|url=http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/news/washington/columnists/tgillman/stories/051108dnnattexwatch.ed8bfa78.html|title=Clinton supporter's plan to stay quiet ends loudly|work=[[Dallas Morning News]]|date=May 11, 2008}}</ref>\n\n;Republican primary race\nIn 2007, Olson announced he would run for the Republican nomination in the 22nd District.  He was one of 10 Republicans in the field.  Also running were Sekula-Gibbs, former [[Pasadena, Texas]] mayor John Manlove, former [[Sugar Land]] mayor [[Dean Hrbacek]], [[Texas House of Representatives|State Representative]] [[Robert Talton]], Senior District Judge [[James D. Squier|Jim Squier]], [[Texas State Board of Education]] member Cynthia Dunbar, and three minor candidates. Sekula-Gibbs won the first round with 30%. Olson finished second, with 21%. As Sekula-Gibbs finished well short of the majority needed to win the nomination outright, Olson and Sekula-Gibbs advanced to a runoff in April.<ref name=\"TSS_Rep\">{{cite web|accessdate=March 6, 2008|url=http://enr.sos.state.tx.us/enr/mar04_135_state.htm|title=2008 Republican Party Primary Election Returns|publisher=Texas Secretary of State's Office|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080313053200/http://enr.sos.state.tx.us/enr/mar04_135_state.htm|archivedate=March 13, 2008|deadurl=yes}}</ref><ref name=HoustonChronicle_Bernstein_20080305>{{cite news|last=Bernstein|first=Alan|title=Congressional District 22: Sekula Gibbs, Olson set up runoff battle for House seat|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|date=March 5, 2008|url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/politics/5596522.html}}</ref> Sekula-Gibbs criticized Olson as \"a Washington insider ... [who] moved here just six months ago to run.\"<ref name=KRIV_20080408>{{cite news|title=Olson Wins Run-Off Elections|publisher=[[KRIV (TV)|Fox 26]]|date=April 8, 2008|url=http://www.myfoxhouston.com/myfox/pages/News/Politics/Detail?contentId=6234304&version=13&locale=EN-US&layoutCode=TSTY&pageId=3.14.1|accessdate=May 25, 2008}}</ref> Nevertheless, 12 of Texas' 19 Republican congressmen endorsed Olson in the primary.<ref name=HoustonChronicle_Bernstein_20080306>{{cite news|first=Alan|last=Bernstein|title=A congressional chorus backs Olson in 22nd District runoff|url=http://blogs.chron.com/txpotomac/2008/03/a_congressional_chorus_backs_o.html|work=Texas on the Potomac|publisher=[[Houston Chronicle]]|date=March 6, 2008|accessdate=May 25, 2008}}</ref>\n\nOlson won the April 8 runoff in a rout with 69 percent of the vote to Sekula-Gibbs' 31 percent.<ref name=TheHill_Blake_20080408>{{cite news|first=Aaron|last=Blake|title=Olson tops Sekula Gibbs in Texas runoff|url=http://thehill.com/campaign-2008/olson-tops-sekula-gibbs-in-texas-runoff-2008-04-08.html|work=The Hill|date=April 8, 2008|accessdate=June 7, 2008|quote='Nick Lampson better find himself a flashlight because his reelection chances are quickly growing dim', said Ken Spain, a spokesman for the National Republican Congressional Committee, adding that 'Pete Olson has proven himself to be one of the top Republican challengers in the country and we believe he has exactly what it takes to win in November.'}}</ref><ref name=CBSNews_Kraushaar_20080408b>{{cite news|last=Kraushaar|first=Josh|title=Olson Wins Texas Runoff, Will Face Lampson|publisher=[[CBS News]]|date=April 8, 2008|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2008/04/08/politics/politico/thecrypt/main4002726.shtml|accessdate=May 25, 2008}}</ref>\n\n;General election race\nOlson faced Lampson in the general election, and John Wieder, the [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]] candidate. Many election experts considered the race one of the best opportunities for the Republicans to pick up a Democratic seat. [[Hastings Wyman]]'s ''[[Southern Political Report]]'' placed the race on its watch list because the roots of the district are solidly Republican, and Lampson won the seat with only 52 percent against a write-in candidate.<ref name=SouthernPoliticalReport_Wyman_20080526>{{cite news|first=Hastings|last=Wyman|title=Dixie's Competitive Congressional Districts|work=Southern Political Report|publisher=Internet News Agency|date=May 26, 2008|url=http://www.southernpoliticalreport.com/storylink_526_410.aspx|accessdate=June 4, 2008|quote=Tom DeLay's (R) old district might return to its roots this fall, since first year incumbent Nick Lampson (D) won in 2006 against a write-in opponent by a mere 52%. Lampson is facing ex-US Senate aide Pete Olson, a GOP-establishment favorite.}}</ref> On June 20, 2008, the ''[[Washington Post]]'''s \"The Fix\" commented on the congressional race: \"it's hard to see Rep. Nick Lampson (D) winning reelection. Lampson's slim hopes got even slimmer\" with the nomination of Olson.<ref name=WashingtonPost_Cillizza_20080620>{{cite news|first=Chris|last=Cillizza|title=The Line: Generic Ballot Distress for House GOP|work=Washington Post|date=June 20, 2008|url=http://blog.washingtonpost.com/thefix/2008/06/the_friday_house_line_generic.html?hpid=topnews|accessdate=June 25, 2008}}</ref> Olson and Lampson agreed to a debate of the issues on October 20, 2008 in [[Rosenberg, Texas]].\n\n;Fundraising efforts\nAt the end of March 2008, Olson's campaign was technically in debt, with almost $128,000 on hand and a debt to the candidate, who provided a personal loan of $175,000.<ref name=HoustonChronicle_Bernstein_20080605>{{cite news|first=Alan|last=Bernstein|title=Cheney to raise funds in Houston for Olson, state GOP|work=Houston Chronicle|date=June 5, 2008|url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/metropolitan/5820770.html|accessdate=June 6, 2008|quote=Cheney, who has extremely low approval ratings in voter surveys and was criticized in former Bush press secretary [[Scott McClellan|Scott McClellan's]] new book, is more of an asset for Olson as a money magnet than as a campaigner, [[University of Houston]] political scientist Richard Murray said.}}</ref>\n\nOn June 5, 2008, outgoing [[Vice President]] [[Dick Cheney]] visited Houston to raise money for Olson's congressional campaign.<ref name=DallasNews_Gillman_20080601>{{cite news|first=Todd|last=Gillman|title=Cheney could be charm or curse in GOP's bid to regain DeLay's seat|work=Dallas Morning News|date=June 1, 2008|url=http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/news/washington/columnists/tgillman/stories/DN-texwatch_01nat.ART.State.Edition1.46c718a.html |accessdate=June 4, 2008|quote=[Cheney's visit is] not bad for a first-time candidate who's basically broke in his bid to unseat Rep. Nick Lampson, D-Stafford, though Democrats call it a sign of desperation.}}</ref><ref name=RealClearPolitics_Wilson_20080607>{{cite news|first=Reid|last=Wilson|title=Strategy Memo: Obama's The Boss|work=Politics Nation|publisher=RealClearPolitics|date=June 6, 2008|url=http://www.realclearpolitics.com/politics_nation/2008/06/strategy_memo_obamas_the_boss.html|accessdate=June 7, 2008}}</ref> The event took place at the home of Houston billionaire [[Dan Duncan]]. From July 1 to September 30, 2008, Olson raised more money than Lampson, $312,700 to $149,000. In the November 2008 election, Olson defeated Lampson with 53 percent of the vote to Lampson's 45%. He won four of the district's five counties.<ref>[http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/25382423/race/house/#District_22 Texas House results by county], msnbc.msn.com; accessed January 18, 2017.</ref>\n\n====Election of 2010====\nOlson won re-election in 2010 with 67 percent of the vote against Democratic challenger [[Kesha Rogers]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/ELECTION/2010/results/state/#val=TX|work=CNN|title=State Results \u2013 Election Center 2010 \u2013 Elections & Politics from CNN.com|accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Election of 2014====\nIn the November 4 general election, Briscoe polled 3,377 votes (53.2 percent) to defeat his intraparty rival, Mark Gibson, who received 2,967 votes (46.8 percent). Briscoe is a son of the late Harris County [[District Attorney]] Frank Briscoe, who was twice defeated in a bid for mayor of Houston and lost the 1966 race in [[Texas' 7th congressional district]] to future President [[George Herbert Walker Bush]]. He is a cousin of the late [[governor of Texas|Governor]] [[Dolph Briscoe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archrecord.construction.com/people/profiles/archives/0207profile.asp|title=Frank \"Chip\" Briscoe: Texan, preservationist, activist|publisher=''Architectural Record''|accessdate=March 9, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/Ex-DA-Frank-Briscoe-legal-heavyweight-for-1689920.php|title=Ex-DA Frank Briscoe, legal heavyweight for decades, dies at 84, January 5, 2011|publisher=''Houston Chronicle''|accessdate=March 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Election of 2016====\nOlson won his fifth term in the House in the general election held on November 8, 2016. He polled 181,864 votes (59.2 percent) to 123,670 (40.5 percent) for his Democratic opponent, Democrat Mark Gibson.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elections.sos.state.tx.us/elchist319_state.htm|title=Election Results|date=November 8, 2016|publisher=Texas Secretary of State|accessdate=December 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===House tenure===\nDuring the 2008 campaign, Olson claimed he was a better fit for the district than Lampson. Olson told ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' reporter Leslie Eaton that \"I have conservative values, and he (Lampson) doesn't.\" <ref name=WSJ_Eaton_20080721>{{cite news|first=Leslie|last=Eaton|title=GOP Goes on Offensive For DeLay's Old Seat|work=Wall Street Journal|date=July 21, 2008|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB121660293928869273?mod=googlenews_wsj|accessdate=August 10, 2008}}</ref> Indeed, not long after being sworn in, Olson joined the [[Republican Study Committee]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|author=|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/|format=|publisher=Republican Study Committee|date=|accessdate=January 2, 2018}}</ref> a caucus of conservative House Republicans. Olson opposes the current incarnation of Interstate 69, which since 2002 has been part of Governor [[Rick Perry]]'s controversial [[Trans-Texas Corridor]], a project [[Phil Gramm]] did not provide funding for as a U.S. Senator. The previous incarnation of I-69 (which Gramm did fund) was slated to go through the current U.S. Highway 59 which passes through Houston and outlying suburbs such as Sugar Land and [[Humble, Texas|Humble]]. On July 24, 2013, Olson voted to continue funding [[National Security Agency|NSA]] surveillance.<ref>[http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2013/roll412.xml Olson profile], clerk.house.gov; accessed January 18, 2017.</ref>\n\nIn mid-November 2013, Olson led a group of 19 other Republican congressmen in an effort to impeach Attorney General [[Eric Holder]], charging that Holder had refused to comply with a subpoena issued by the [[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform]] in 2011 and that he had failed to enforce laws defending the [[Defense of Marriage Act]] (which had been declared unconstitutional by the Supreme Court)<ref>[http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/190219-gop-members-seek-to-impeach-holder \"Twenty House Republicans call for Holder impeachment\"], thehill.com, November 13, 2014.</ref> or mandatory minimum sentencing for low-level drug offenders. Olson also charged that Holder had failed to enforce the [[Controlled Substances Act]] by not suing Washington and Colorado for deciding to regulate rather than criminalize marijuana.<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/11/14/eric-holder-impeachment_n_4276097.html \"House Republicans Want To Impeach Eric Holder For Refusing To Defend Unconstitutional Law\"], huffingtonpost.com; retrieved November 17, 2013.</ref>\n\nOn June 9, 2017, Olson stated during a radio broadcast that former President Bill Clinton had admitted to the murder of White House aide Vincent Foster and had threatened former Attorney General Loretta Lynch with similar violence if she did not drop an investigation of former Secretary of State Hillary Clinton. When subsequently asked for evidence to support his claims, Olson said: \"In my discussion about Loretta Lynch and Vince Foster, I took the accusations a step too far. I regret my choice of words.\" <ref>texastribune.org/2017/06/20/congressman-says-comments-about-clintons-were-step-too-far/</ref>\n\nOn August 15, 2018, Olson incorrectly claimed in a speech that \"[on] September 11th, 2001, 3000 innocent Americans were killed by terrorists from Pakistan.\" In fact, none of the 9/11 hijackers were of Pakistani origin.  Congressman Olson later told a reporter that he had misspoken when he made the claim.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archrecord.construction.com/people/profiles/archives/0207profile.asp|title=U.S. Rep. Pete Olson \u2018accidentally\u2019 blamed Pakistanis for 9/11 terrorist attack|publisher=''Houston Chronicle''|accessdate=September 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce|Committee on Energy and Commerce]]'''\n** [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Commerce, Manufacturing and Trade|Subcommittee on Commerce, Manufacturing and Trade]]\n** [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Energy and Power|Subcommittee on Energy and Power]]\n\n===Caucus Memberships===\n[[Congressional Constitution Caucus]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://congressionalconstitutioncaucus-garrett.house.gov/about-us/membership|format=|publisher=Congressional Constitution Caucus|date=|accessdate=May 8, 2018}}</ref>  Aerospace Caucus, General Aviation Caucus, Coal Caucus, Balanced Budget Amendment Caucus, Natural Gas Caucus, National Guard and Reserve Caucus, Beef Caucus, Gulf Coast Caucus, Cystic Fibrosis Caucus, Taiwan Caucus, Ports to Plains Caucus, Diabetes Caucus, Rice Caucus, Johnson Caucus, [[Congressional Arts Caucus]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Membership|author=|url=https://artscaucus-slaughter.house.gov/membership|format=|publisher=Congressional Arts Caucus|date=|accessdate=March 13, 2018}}</ref> [[Congressional Western Caucus]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://westerncaucus.house.gov/about/membership.htm|format=|publisher=Congressional Western Caucus|date=|accessdate=18 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Political positions ==\n\n=== Anti-Transgender civil rights ===\nOlson sponsored the Civil Rights Uniformity Act of 2016 (HR 5812) which would strictly limit the definition of gender to the person's biological gender assigned at birth for the purposes of interpreting federal civil rights laws, federal administrative agency regulations, and other federal guidance. The proposed legislation would effectively remove those people whose gender identity does not match their biological gender as a protected class, but the bill died in committee.<ref>{{USBill|114|H.R.|5812|pipe=Text of the Civil Rights Uniformity Act of 2016 |site=yes}}</ref> In 2017, Olson reintroduced the bill as the [[Civil Rights Uniformity Act of 2017]] (HR 2796) with language identical to HR 5812, including a reference to \"President Barack Obama's administration\" which had, in the bill's language, \"attempted to replace the word 'sex' with the phrase 'gender identity' for purposes of Federal antidiscrimination law and policy through a series of unilateral executive actions\" and further, that \"the Obama administration's actions are an affront to the rule of law, the separation of powers, the will of the people, language, history, safety, privacy, and biological realities.\"<ref name=115HR2796>{{USBill|115|H.R.|2796|pipe=Text of the Civil Rights Uniformity Act of 2017 |site=yes}}</ref> Olson argued that \"only Congress has the constitutional authority to change laws\" and that interpreting \"sex\" to include \"gender identity\" was not the original or explicit intent of the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/congress-blog/judicial/304350-restoring-the-constitutional-roles-of-the-executive-legislative |title=Editorial: Restoring the constitutional roles of the executive, legislative branches |author=Olson, Pete |date=November 4, 2016 |publisher=The Hill |accessdate=September 6, 2017}}</ref> Critics noted the effect of stripping federal protections from transgender people would only exacerbate existing discrimination and could lead to \"a declaration of an open season for discrimination against transgender people.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://broadly.vice.com/en_us/article/vbvwk9/insane-federal-bill-would-strip-trans-people-of-their-civil-rights |title=Insane Federal Bill Would Strip Trans People of Their Civil Rights |author=Scaccia, Annamarya |date=August 3, 2017 |publisher=Vice |website=Broadly |accessdate=September 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn a press release following the introduction of HR 2796, Olson stated that gender identity should not be treated as a protected class unless explicitly established by Congress. \"The Obama Administration strongly overreached by unilaterally redefining the definition of \"sex\" with respect to the Civil Rights Act outside of the lawmaking process. We must reject the notion of false power stolen from Congress by a White House seeking to impose social policy on America. The Founding Fathers never intended unelected bureaucrats in federal agencies to make sweeping changes to the definition of gender.\"<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://olson.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/house-members-act-to-restore-congressional-authority-on-transgender |title=House Members Act to Restore Congressional Authority on Transgender Definition |author= |date=June 7, 2017 |publisher=Office of Congressman Pete Olson, Representing the 22nd District of Texas |accessdate=August 1, 2017}}</ref> The arguments were consistent with Olson's prior statements following the introduction of HR 5812, which stated it \"will ensure that gender identity is not treated as a protected class in Federal Law or Policy without the affirmative approval of the people's representatives in Congress\".<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://olson.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/olson-bill-puts-congress-in-driver-seat-on-transgender-definition |title=Olson Bill Puts Congress in Driver Seat on Transgender Definition |author= |date=August 3, 2016 |publisher=Office of Congressman Pete Olson, Representing the 22nd District of Texas |accessdate=September 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=https://olson.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/new-gsa-bathroom-rule-further-evidence-olson-bill-needed |title=New GSA Bathroom Rule Further Evidence Olson Bill Needed |author= |date=August 18, 2016 |publisher=Office of Congressman Pete Olson, Representing the 22nd District of Texas |accessdate=September 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ {{ushr|Texas|22}}: 2008\u20132016 results<ref>{{cite news |title=2008 General Election Results |url=http://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/nov04_141_race22.htm?x=0&y=268&id=429 |work=Secretary of State |publisher=State of Texas |date=November 4, 2008 |accessdate=November 6, 2008}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}\n</ref>\n!|Year\n!\n!|Re